std::packaged_task is a container wrapper that binds any callable target (like a function, lambda, or member function) so that it can be executed asynchronously, 
automatically caching its return value or thrown exception inside a std::future.

Move-Only: You cannot copy a std::packaged_task. You must transfer its ownership using std::move().
Single Execution: You can only invoke the task object once. If you try to run it a second time, it will throw a std::future_error with a broken promise error.

Why Use std::packaged_task Instead of std::async?
Feature            std::async                          std::packaged_task
Thread Management  Controlled by runtime library      Manual (You choose the thread/pool)
Execution Timing   Starts immediately (usually)       Starts exactly when you call task()
Best Used For      Quick, simple parallel tasks       Writing custom Thread Pools or schedulers


#include <iostream>
#include <future>
#include <thread>

// 1. Define a basic worker function
int calculate_sum(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    // 2. Wrap the function in a packaged_task.
    // The template signature must match the function signature.
    std::packaged_task<int(int, int)> task(calculate_sum);

    // 3. Extract the future before moving the task
    std::future<int> fut = task.get_future();

    // 4. Pass the task to a thread to execute it.
    // std::packaged_task is move-only, so you must use std::move.
    std::thread t(std::move(task), 10, 20);

    // 5. Do other work on main thread, then get the result
    int result = fut.get(); // Blocks until thread 't' finishes the task
    std::cout << "The sum is: " << result << "\n";

    t.join();
    return 0;
}


